docs.abstract: What does it mean for Nike to align itself with Colin Kaepernick?
docs.snippet: What does it mean for Nike to align itself with Colin Kaepernick?
docs.lead_paragraph: Last fall, Nike released a groundbreaking ad featuring the former N.F.L. quarterback Colin Kaepernick. His kneeling protest, which started in 2016 as a response to police brutality, was reinterpreted by social media, celebrities and Nike itself to mean something that doesn’t always match the intention of his original protest. So what does it say that a multinational corporation has aligned itself with a social movement? And are we O.K. with this form of “Kaepitalism”?

docs.abstract: Mr. Heyward became an activist after his 13-year-old son, who was playing with a toy gun, was killed by a police officer in Brooklyn in 1994.
docs.snippet: Mr. Heyward became an activist after his 13-year-old son, who was playing with a toy gun, was killed by a police officer in Brooklyn in 1994.
docs.lead_paragraph: One September evening in 1994, Nicholas Heyward Jr., 13, was playing cops and robbers with friends on a rooftop at the Gowanus Houses, the Brooklyn housing project where he lived. The boys, carrying toy guns, decided to go back inside and rushed down the stairs, jostling one another.

headline.main: Nicholas Heyward Sr., 61, Dies; Spoke Out Against Police Brutality
headline.print_headline: Nicholas Heyward Sr., 61, Police Brutality Protester

docs.abstract: The police claimed Naqeebullah Mehsud, a shopkeeper and aspiring model, had really been a dangerous militant. Now a court has cleared him posthumously.

docs.lead_paragraph: ISLAMABAD, Pakistan — A Pakistani judge on Thursday formally dismissed terrorism charges against a man whose killing in a police encounter last year threw a spotlight on extrajudicial killings and police brutality in the country.

headline.main: Aspiring Model Killed by Pakistani Police Is Cleared of Charges

docs.abstract: The making of Sheila Pree Bright’s photo-mural of black women who had lost their sons gave a group of mothers a chance to tell their stories.
docs.snippet: The making of Sheila Pree Bright’s photo-mural of black women who had lost their sons gave a group of mothers a chance to tell their stories.
docs.lead_paragraph: The past informs the present in the work of Sheila Pree Bright, who has been photographing the Black Lives Matter movement since 2014. As an artist who draws connections between today’s young activists and their civil rights forebears, she seemed a natural choice to be among 11 socially conscious artists selected to create murals highlighting Atlanta’s past, present and future in time for the Super Bowl, when the city will be in the spotlight.

headline.main: From the Civil Rights Movement to Black Lives Matter: Honoring Black Mothers Who Lost Their Sons
